description.text:
Bowden Clamp (K.I.S.S. method) for Ultimaker
Well! It happened to us too! A couple of prints and then the Bowden Tube popped up and that was all she wrote! Searching this site and we found the solution (we thought) which is Owen's Bowden Clamp for Ultimaker (Heater End) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11864 but then Catch 22 kicked in. How to use the solution when you can't make the solution, (because the Bowden thingy has popped up and won't stay in because............) Ok! Another solution needed. So applying the K.I.S.S. (Keep it simple, stupid!) method, here it is.

Instructions: Cut a thin aluminium plate (or in keeping with the Ultimaker style use a scrap wood piece from your UM build) that is shaped to fit over the corner of the Heater module. Drill a hole in the plate at its corner so that the thumb screw can be inserted. Drill another hole to locate the Bowden Tube snuggly and at such a distance from 1st hole that when assembled, tightening the thumb screw will cause the Bowden Tube to be pushed against the side of the original hole in the wooden plate on the top of the heater module and this will clamp the Bowden tube securely. As added security retain the circlip arrangement of the initial build.
Sorry, can't supply dimensions as its all joined together and we ain't pulling it apart, but just picture if you can, the long side (hypotenuse) of a right angle triangle with the two holes in it acting a lever to nip that tube in place!

I was quite surprised to find out how expensive assistive technology is. A mechanical braille embosser cost over a 1000$USD and an electronic goes from 3000$ up to 5000$. I tough about making one for a friend but I couldn't find a DIY version, so I decided to make one myself. This isn’t, by any means, a finish product. By making the machine an open source project, I am hoping others will improve the design. In a near future, with the help of others makers, OpenBraille will reduce the cost of these printers and it will allow anyone with a visual imparity to read and write. So, if you know someone, if you are a maker, if you are curious or if you want to help out, please feel free to follow this tutorial and help me built a community around OpenBraille.
The encoder is pretty much the heart of the embosser. Most of the commercial machines emboss the dots by impacting the sheet. Because it’s harder to build a precise machine out of 3D printed parts, I designed a different system. Instead of impacting and applying all the energy in a single hit, OpenBraille uses a physical encoder and a roller. This way, the embossing is gradually done and the parts can be easily printed.

Once the intake is printed run a 5mm drill through the input shaft hole, and remove supports, then I cut a 30 by 50mm hole in the base of the hole (ended up being closer to ~53mm to get the intake to fit) when installed correctly the flange at the bottom by the intake grate should be on the outside of the boat. Put it on the rod and screw everything back. For the Z screw the chain end to the hole(s) of (I think) the filament holder. Rewiring your cables might take some nerves. title: Anet A8 adjustable height Modular Extruder

description.text:
Features
-The best thing about this is that you can adjust the extruder height while printing with just one screw, that way you can leave the hotbed in a fix position, this way you don't need a sensor in the extruder
-Extruder tray allows you to remove the extruder for maintenance and replace it with another extruder really quick, just print as many trays as extruders you have, and don't use the heat block screw so you can remove the heat bar easily, I been working without the screw for a while and never had a problem
-The extruder is in the same position as the original mount, so you don't have to change anything in the firmware

Instructions:

  • Use two nuts to attach the extruder and push fitting, the nut on top should hold the push fitting and the extruder tube, the nut in the bottom is for extra firmness
  • Attach the printing fan to the tray support in the hole, you will need to make the hole a little bigger with an awl.
  • Put a nut in the tray support and a screw in the support base with a spring (all of this parts from the hot bed support, you wont need them in the hot bed anymore)
  • Slide the tray support in the tray rail making sure to screw the screw in the nut. Now you can use a screw driver to adjust the extruder height.
  • Adjust the z-endstop and hotbed, you can leave the hotbed in a fix position
  • Attach the mount to the linear bearing, you can use a belt holder if you want or the two crews

Known Issues
-Some screws are hard to tie because is too close to the tray rail, I'll fix this in the next version
-Push fitting is a little hard to screw
-Extruder tray don't slide smoothly, the same with the tray support in the base, a little sandpaper work can fix this.

In my prototype the extruder tray is not all the way in because i had issues printing (i didn't use support)

I'm using the print fan as heat dissipator fan, because i don't see too much benefits of cooling the print while printing, anyway I'll think how to implement the other fan as printing cooler, but this one is the best for the heat dissipator because you can move it away or close to the dissipator easy.

description.text:
Since I couldn't find any decent desktop spool holder that would fit printing on the Flashforge Finder, I decided to dive in and design one myself. Whole assembly doesn't require any glue and it fits really snuggly together. You might notice a wobble once all is assembled, but it's ok, this has been designed so that the spool adds rigidity to it. Once the filament spool is on, it's solid.

I included two different bars, standard and if your spool has a slightly higher diameter then you can print out a thicker version that will give you some extra clearance. Bar has inbuilt threads that work well with the threads inside of the screw caps.

As for the printing itself:

  1. Print without supports (unless you print the thicker bar, then you might need some);
  2. For the full assembly, print: 2 sides, 2 feet, 2 screw caps and 1 bar;
  3. Raft is recommended to avoid warping, especially for feet;
  4. Print any resolution you'd like (I printed mine at 0.3 layer to save on time and filament);
  5. Print on 10%+ infill (the more infill, the tougher the part will be, but the more filament will be used to print it, and it will add time too).
  6. On the Flashforge Finder, print sides separately, but the bar, feet and caps can be printed simultaneously)

Enjoy!

title: LACK Attack #1: Stack the Lack (aka The Lack Stack Adapter)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I don't expect many to follow this, but my plan is to post my journey into printer enclosures and expand beyond my current "it sits on the table" model...

Wanting to learn and build on what others have done, I decided to start a series of "things" to chronicle my "accidental" (aka the wife doesn't know yet) foyer into printer enclosures in hopes I can help others looking to take the next step, as well to learn from others that have that might see this and provide some help along the way.

It all started one night when my wife went to work and I decided to visit IKEA looking for the new TRÅDFRI gateway and bulbs... "Somehow" 4 or 5 (maybe 6) LACK end tables also fell onto my cart...
I thought: "I think I've seen others use these for enclosures, well its too hard to put them back now, I guess they're coming home with me...."
Muahahahaha.... ;)

We'll see how long this series of builds lasts, it might not last past the morning when she gets home, we'll have to see...

As always, comments are greatly appreciated, in this case direction and pitfalls to watch for are also appreciated, If you've been here done this and have a better way please let me know.

without further adieu....

Attack 1: STACK THE LACK

After assembling 5 LACK tables, stacking them wasn't that much fun, they didn't want to stay in place, so..... I searched Thingyverse and found.... way too many ideas and options....

So I built my own...

NOTE: SAVE THE SPARE LEGS! If your following this build, you need them for LACK ATTACK #4.

Based on a number of other builds (its really a simple part) I put together a quick Lack Stack adapter. It'll likely (definitely) be replaced in the (near) future but its a starting point for this series of builds.

A simple corner coupler, it locks the upper LACK into the lower LACK, so you can built a LACK STACK.

Next:
Attack #2: Lets Caster the Lack Stack...

I switched over to Cura and its 0.40mm settings with 0% infill, once it got past the first 3 layers I turned the speed on the printer up to 175%, each set afterwards only took ~30 minutes to complete.

description.text:
I do quite a lot of work with circuit boards and small mechanical parts and was finding the 'helping hands' crocodile clip type tool too fiddly and a bench vice too big for my needs, so after a bit of thought I designed my own light duty 3D printed vice with a novel tension / release method.

This vice is ideal for holding small parts or circuit boards up to 70mm (2 3/4") while you adjust / solder / glue etc.

To clamp insert the workpiece into the jaws, pull the elastic cord through the slot to a suitable tension then pull the cord down to lock.

To release simply pull the cord up. The tension on the elastic is eased and the workpiece freed.

After a bit of practice it's a matter of a couple of seconds to clamp a workpiece in place.

I've put a more complete write-up of this on Instructables : https://www.instructables.com/id/Quick-Clamp-Release-Vice-Vise/

Notes:

The obvious choice of material for the print (for me, anyway) is PLA, due to its rigidity, 'slippiness' and low shrinkage. Nylon would be stronger but as this is only intended for light use, PLA is adequate for the job.

I printed this onto glass with 3 shells and 40% infill. If your printer has trouble with bridging then support underneath the roof of the 34mm recesses in the base would be a good idea. Mine printed fine without.

Fettling the 3D print

Once assembled the slide is designed to move freely along the base of the vice; the exact dimensions give a 0.2mm clearance between the sliding parts. However you may well find that the slide . . . won't. Fear not, but do not force the parts otherwise they may jam immovably.

First of all, check for bottom layer spread. Also check for over-extrusion at the edges. Once you can feel that things may fit, spray / rub some wax furniture polish onto a cloth and give the sliding parts a wipe. This will make all the difference. Now slowly and carefully work the slide backwards and forwards along the base and you will feel things beginning to ease. On the two I made the slide will move from end to end under gravity alone.

Additional Parts List

6 x 32mm (1 3/8") washers or similar to weight the base.

Small amount of 1mm (1/16") self adhesive neoprene sheet. Neoprene is a dense rubber and should last a while as long as it's not overheated. 1.5mm or 2mm would do equally well.

4 x self adhesive feet. Not vital, but gives more of a non-slip to the vice. Mine came from a small network switch box. Alternatively use a bit of the neoprene mentioned above.

200mm (8") of elastic bungee cord, 3mm (1/8") diameter or so. 3mm is ideal but the gripping method will adapt for a bit thinner or thicker.

Adhesive : Foaming polyurethane Gorilla glue, cyanoacrylate (superglue) or epoxy.

Assembly

1) Cut a strip of neoprene rubber approx 12mm (1/2") wide. I found it's tidier to cut the split piece to size before attaching, rather than attaching then trying to cut out the middle section. Remove the backing and attach to the jaws of the vice.

2) Glue the washers into the recesses in the base of the vice to give it greater stability and a solid feel.

3) Pass the bungee cord through hole in the slide and knot it. A bit of glue will stop the knot from pulling out and keep it in the recess.

4) Pass the other end of the cord through the toggle and knot it so the unstretched length of the cord puts the slide around 3/4 of the way down the base. This will give stop the slide from coming off the end when not in use. Trim off the excess length.

5) Attach the four feet, and you're done. Go and make another one !

Connects Ø4mm tube together for use with resin pump.

Printed on my D7
It's a lot less insulating, but a lot more full of holes!
Standard resolution, 5% infill for my first pass, but feel free to go up to 10% infill for a denser thing!

description.text:
The way the fan is installed on the ANET A8 is a real mess.
In case of clogging, you"ll have to disassemble the whole thing and loose your precious Z-offset calibration...

As many of you, I don't think the heatsink is needed. To work properly a heat sink needs a good contact with the element it has to cool. Here, the heat sink is poorly in contact with the big lower aluminium part of the extruder. The size of this alu part is big enough to act as a pretty good heatsink by itself.
==> you can safely remove the heat sink...

Now we have to support the fan and make it easy to dismount to access to the gears of the extruder.
Many good options are available here on thingiverse using printed parts, magnets or so ...
My solution is for sure the simplest ever using only two M3 threaded rods on which the fan will simply slide... a Keep It Smart and Simple thing !
Replace the two M3 screws at the bottom by two pieces of M3 threaded rods. Tighten the black alu part in position with two nuts on the threaded rods.
Keep the length of the threaded rods long enough to slide the fan on those two rods. The fan will stay in position.
If you need to access to extruder's gears just pull the fan ... Et voilà

If you don't get any threaded rod in your garage, you migth as well use 2 long M3 screws, just remove the heads... If not long enough, connect two of them with a printed tube or glue them with a piece of tube, there is room enough between the fan and the aluminium block and this would act as a fan spacer .

EDIT : I've designed a small cover which acts both as a spacer for the fan and as fan duct avoiding that too much air is blown downwards in direction of the hot end. Just slide the cover on the two M3 rods then slide the fan on top of it.

description.text:
A common problem for people who have recently built an Anet-A8 is getting repeatable alignment of the two Z-axis steppers. Particularly since the X-idler side seems often to bind as it moves up and down.

Here are two tools to help with the alignment and to help check what is going on with calibration.

With steppers disabled, you can use the stand (tool 2) to set both Z-screws with the X-bearing bars at the same height from the base. This should be your 'starting point' before trying any other calibration.

Once this is done, you can use the bridge along with a dial gauge (thing:1935249) to check that the bed/y-bearings are level with respect to the Z-bearings on each side. Due to the arrangement of the bridge, both bed levelling and the position of the Y bearings will have an impact on this (60/40 biased to the bearings) so if you want perfection you need to indicate level with both this tool, and the bed itself with the same settings. Perfection here means readings with less than 0.5mm from one side to the other - you still want to rely on the bed-leveling for the last detail

Finally, with the bridge at the idler side (right), take a dial-gauge reading at home, wind Z up to the maximum print height you're using, and home Z again. Anything more than 0.1mm variation indicates a repeatability problem.

description.text:
I took the idea of the IKEA dome Terrarium and decided to rework it slightly since I wasn't able to get the Moss to survive.

If you print this in PLA do use a lacquer on the inside the dome parts. PLA will expand ever so slightly if exposed to water. This will burst your dome. It happened to me so be careful.

Also the IKEA domes have some variance so use the test object to validate if it fits. Adjust the scad files if it isn't.

I recommend putting 1mm rubber sheet on the bottom of the base to keep it from sliding around.

Update: testing shows that my dome terrarium slowly loses water over time. Add a few tablespoons full every 6 months. I assume the loss is due to expanding/contracting air with temperature changes between day and night slowly "pumping" higher humidity air from the inside to the outside.
You can tell by looking at the condensation that fogs the glass when the plants are doing their thing in light. if there isn't any at all or if you have a plant that needs slightly more then you need to add water.

description.text:
These Straw Connectors can be used to link together straws into big structures. For fun with kids, but also as a frame to wrap in rice-paper and use as lamp-shade, or any other application that needs a light-weight structure.

The files contain a few sample STL files for some possible connectors, but the main source is the OpenSCAD file, which makes it easy to create any size and type you want. See Parameters for details.

The sample files and default parameters are tweaked for use with the big IKEA straws (Sötvatten). Other brands of straws might work just fine.
Because the connectors require a press-fit and straws don't stretch much, an exact size of the connector is quite critical. Different straws and different printers and printer settings may lead to slightly different fit. Print a single XYZ connector first to test-fit, before printing a grid of multiples connectors.

Full disclosure: This is not my own original idea. The concept exists (or has existed) commercially, and there are plenty people tinkering with this on Thingiverse. See my collection of related things here: https://www.thingiverse.com/erie/collections/straw-connectors.
I created my own version, because I wanted to be able to easily tweak the sizes and shapes, and create new types when needed. Also, I discovered that not all straws are created equal. Even the straws from IKEA that I use (Sötvatten), have slightly different diameters for each color straw. This creates the need for very fine tuned sizing, for one connector to work with all color straws.

You probably need a whole lot of connectors to make an interesting structure. To reduce the post-processing time, the model aims to require no support structures and no build plate adhesion (brim/raft/etc). See Print Settings for details.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

No support required
These connectors can be printed without support structures (at normal straw sizes anyway). A straw diameter of 8mm (e.g. IKEA Sötvatten) works great.

No build-plate adhesion required
The model already contains build-plate adhesion structures, that lead to as little as possible post-processing. I added that to the model because the default options in Cura leave to many artifacts that take too long to remove. There is very little play to have a snug fit with the straws.
So, in your slicer you should select "no build plate adhesion". If you have trouble with adhesion, you can add a bit of extra brim. I typically do that for single connectors. If you print multiple connectors at once, in a grid, they are interconnected and have plenty of build-surface area.

Retraction
Enabling retraction is wise, as you want as little artifacts as possible.

Material
I print these in PLA, but I see no reason why ABS woudn't work just as well. You might need to retweak the sizes.

Parameters

These are the most important parameters in the OpenSCAD file, with some explanation what they do. See the OpenSCAD source file for more detailed documentation.

// Sizes of each tube
radiusTip    =  3.85; // Outside part of each tube. 
radiusMid    =  4.0;  // Middel part of each tube. This should be slightly bigger than the straw inner radius, and bigger/equal to the raduisTip 
radiusBase   =  3.95; // Base/Center part, where they connect together
lengthTip    =  5.0;  // 
lengthMid    =  5.0;  //
wallThickness=  0.8;  // Bigger is stronger, but slower print.

//  tubeEndHoleRadius sets the size of the hole in the end of the tube. Choose 0 for completely closed, or "radiusTip-wallThickness" for completely open. Partially closing up the ends helps with keeping the round shape of the tube without having support structures. 
tubeEndHoleRadius = 1.2; // in mm

//  holeTroughBack can be used to string a fishing-wire trough the connector if your construction needs extra tensile strength to stay together (e.g long horizontal spans).
holeTroughBack = true; // true|false

//  FlattenedSides make it easier and cleaner to print without support structures and create beter print bed adhesion. If true, the circomference of the tube will be slightly smaller, you might have to tweak the radii.
flattenSides = true;  // true|false

//  buildPlateAdhesionGrid creates a "1 layer" thick grid of strips underneath the connectors, connection them together and creating a larger surface area to stick to the buildPlate. If you enable this option, you should turn of adhesion in your slicing software. 
buildPlateAdhesionGrid        = true; // true|false

Customizer

I enabled Customizer, but my file doesn't seem completely compatible. I might restructure the source code later, for beter compatibility.

description.text:
I designed this spool holder because I upgraded my printer for dual filament printing.
I love top mounted spool holders but they seem a little flimsy to hold two filament spools.
I need a Hard-Core spool holder for this...

It's designed for 52mm hole spools, the small spacer is for 750g spools (55mm max width) and the large is for 1kg spools (80mm max width).

Each spindle takes two 608Z skateboard bearings.
For the brackets you need 9-M4x10mm socket head cap screws, 9-M4 T-nuts or square nuts,
For the holder you need 3-M4x15mm socket head cap screws, 3-M4 Ny-loc nut, 3-M4 washer.
For the main spindle you need 1-M8x45mm countersunk bolt, 1-M8 Ny-loc nut, 1-M8 washer.
For the spacers you need 1-M8x50mm countersunk bolt, 1-M8 Ny-loc nut, 1-M8 washer.

ATT:
Each spacer prints with the bolt hole closed by two layers for the hexagonal hole to print correctly (see foto).
The tightness of the Ny-loc nut adjusts the drag on the spindle so the spools don't unwind by themselves.
The spools have to be mounted with opposite feed directions (see last foto).

title: Monoprice MP Select Mini V2 40mm Fan Shroud (Shortened)

description.text:
This model was a variation made on thing 2448223. If you have an unmodified extruder assembly, I would suggest using the other one instead.

This is a replacement for the fan shroud that comes mounted to the hot end of Monoprice Select Mini printers. This new shroud supplies the printed parts and heat break with superior cooling and allows for the mounting of a 40mm fan.

This model was designed to work with m4 bolts which means that whatever 40mm fan you have should have 4mm diameter screw holes in it. I have attached a stl file with a 3D printable bolt in case you do not own one of the correct length.

The clearance between the bottom of this shroud and the print bed/printed part is about 1mm. Thanks to the super simple and repeatable mounting of this shroud, this value should be fairly consistent for everyone who uses the model.

This shroud is even easier to mount than the stock shroud that comes on the printer. While the model still uses the same retaining springs, the tabs are a little bit easier to get the spring around and the flat piece at the top of the model forces the assembly to stay in place after the first spring is attached.

This design is still a work in progress and as such, comments about possible improvements and any questions you may have are welcome.

description.text: Why yet-yet another? Well, there's tons for the 30A version of this PSU (various clones: Supernight, Mean Well, and several noname), but very few for the (fanless) 20A version. The one I have is the 12V 20A Supernight but it should fit several others (check images). This design is inspired by a couple of others in terms of features, but is done from scratch. OpenSCAD sources included.

Bill of materials (links to what I used, but you can substitute):
  • Voltmeter
  • Ammeter (see note below)
  • Rocker switch
  • Large grommet
  • Small grommet
  • Grounded power cord
  • Zipties (to secure cables behind grommets)
  • Wire
  • Crimp-on lug connectors (if you want)
    • Caution: Linked ammeter is under-rated for this PSU in general (10A vs 20A); however in my application the load does not exceed about 8.5-9A. If your load is higher, you will want to substitute an ammeter with a different shunt (such as this one, although fitting the shunt might be nontrivial; alternatively, just edit the SCAD source to remove ammeter cutout). Instructions:
  • Print back cover (and, optionally, arm and front cover). I used a brim and enclosure. Since the back cover was a pretty long print @.2mm, I still got some minor warping and very tiny layer gaps in corners, which I friction welded just to minimize chance they'll delaminate in the future.
  • (Optional) Install grommets.
  • Tap holes for meters, and install meters.
  • Wire rocker switch and thread wires through mounting hole, but do not clip it into the cutout yet if you will be using the retaining hook (back arm). Otherwise the arm will hit the switch and you won't be able to slide the cover on.
  • Solder and connect wires. Mostly common sense. I guess you have two options for the voltmeter: (i) in parallel to PSU+ and PSU- terminals, or (ii) in parallel to PSU+ and ammeter shunt input wire. Not sure if it makes any difference (shunt voltage drop should be tiny), but I went for the second.
  • (Optional) Install zipties on cables behind grommets, for strain relief.
  • Connect all wires to PSU terminals. At this point, everything should be ready so you can slide cover onto PSU. If you want to adjust the voltage trimpot and haven't done so already, now would be a good time.
  • (Optional) Install back arm retaining hook. Press-fit an M3 nut on the arm with your soldering iron, then hook the arm over the PCB standoff (it's dimensioned tightly, you need to slide-and-twist on, and you may need also to file arm slightly). Slide back cover partially onto unit. You may have to guide the back arm into place with a screwdriver through the rocker switch mounting hole. Once in place, screw back arm onto cover.
  • Clip rocker switch onto cover. This requires some care, as it's possible to delaminate the part if you apply excessive force. Insert one side first, then the other. If switch is too tight (also depends on printer calibration), file the hole edges slightly.
  • Secure cover with a screw on the side of the PSU. You can use just this screw, and skip the back arm if you find installation too finicky (also: installing is ok, but removing is quite tricky, with rocker switch clipped on -- so, if you plan to remove cover often, it's best to leave arm off, or edit source and move rocker cutout ~5mm to the right).
  • (Optional) Front cover just slides on (it's only purpose is to make the bottom even, you can skip if you want).
    • For a DC connector you can use whatever you wish (in the picture it's a couple of quick-connects I had lying around), or you can do just bare wire.

title: Improved fan duct and inductive probe holder for Voron X-carriage

description.text:
I upgraded my Voron to the volcom8190 X-carraige system which allowed use of 12 mm inductive sensor and 2x 4010 blower fans. The overall design was very good but I noticed a few points that could be improved.

I added Solidworks files for easy remixing.

E(08.11.2017): added v2.2 fan duct which directs most of the air to the part and not to the hotend. It has holes for m2 screws (because of 3dsway fans).

Volcom8190's original design spread the airflow from the 4010 to the quite big area. This would have been ok, if the cheap chinesium 4010 fans would be powerful, but they aren't. My first attempt to get a better cooling performance out of this solution was to add a step up converter which enabled me to run 12V fans with 24V. That kind of improved the situation but after a while fans started to make strange noises, which is obviously because they are not designed for that high rpm that 24V forces them to run.
Meanwhile I searched for a quality 4010 blower fan which i did not find. I managed to find one supplier who offers fans with almost double the cfm than the Gstime ones that i have. When they arrive I'll confirm if they're any good.
It came to quite clear that in order to get better cooling I have to focus the weak airflow to the place where I really need it. After a few tries I came up with the design presented here. It moves the opening closer and lower to the nozzle and concentrates airflow to the right below to the nozzle.
Comparison of the cooling performance is given below. Open image in new tab for zoom-in action!

Unfortunately I happened to have different length 12mm inductive probe than volcom8190. So I made a design that enables to use shorter probe that i have. On the way I shortened the cable holder (which was too long for my needs) and added a small slabs that will prevent the small amount of rocking back and forth that original design had. Also I managed to move the sensor a bit closer to the nozzle (Y offset is 54 mm compared to the original's 61 mm).

I just edit the script to power off the led when the RPI is done (and not when it is not powered, as the original script is doing)

#!/bin/python
# Script permettant de gerer l'alummage et l'extinction d'un RPI

# Version V2.0

# A l'allumage :
#   - Ventilateur en marche
#   - Led en marche
# A l'extinction :
#   - Ventilateur a l'arret
#   - Led a l'arret
# by jeff38100

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time
import os

# Use the Broadcom SOC Pin numbers
# Setup the Pin with Internal pullups enabled and PIN in reading mode.

#-------------Declaration des pins
pin_led = 24            # Numero de pin de la LED, CHANGE HERE
pin_button_off = 23         # Numero de pin du boutton, CHANGE HERE
pin_fan = 18            # Numero de pin du ventilateur, CHANGE HERE

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)      # On initialize les GPIO par les Numeros de GPIO

#-------------Declaration des variables
etat_led = False        # Image de la led
etat_button_off = False     # Image du boutton
etat_fan = False        # Image du ventilateur
etat_rpi = False        # Image du RPI

#-------------Declaration des pins d'entree

GPIO.setup(pin_button_off, GPIO.IN, pull_up_down = GPIO.PUD_UP)  #Bouton OFF

#-------------Declaration des pins de sortie

GPIO.setup(pin_led, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(pin_fan, GPIO.OUT)

#-------------Les fonctions

#Procedure d'arret
def Shutdown(channel):
    GPIO.output(pin_led,GPIO.LOW)   #Extinction de la led
    GPIO.output(pin_fan,GPIO.LOW)   #Extinction du ventilateur

    os.system("sudo shutdown -h now")   #Arret system

# Action sur detection du bouton OFF
GPIO.add_event_detect(pin_button_off, GPIO.FALLING, callback = Shutdown, bouncetime = 2000)

#-------------Start
GPIO.output(pin_fan,GPIO.HIGH)  #Allumage du ventilateur
etat_fan = True

GPIO.output(pin_led,GPIO.HIGH)  #Allumage de la led
etat_led = True

#-------------Update
while 1:

    time.sleep(1)           #Attente 1 secondes

#!/bin/python
# Simple script for shutting down the raspberry Pi at the press of a button.
# by Inderpreet Singh

# Version V1.0

import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time
import os

# Use the Broadcom SOC Pin numbers
# Setup the Pin with Internal pullups enabled and PIN in reading mode.

# On initialize les GPIO par les Numeros de GPIO
GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BCM)  

#Declaration du PIN 23 en entree
GPIO.setup(23, GPIO.IN, pull_up_down = GPIO.PUD_UP) 

#Declaration du PIN 24 en sortie
GPIO.setup(24, GPIO.OUT)

# Our function on what to do when the button is pressed
def Shutdown(channel):
    GPIO.output(24,GPIO.LOW)
    os.system("sudo shutdown -h now")

# Add our function to execute when the button pressed event happens
GPIO.add_event_detect(23, GPIO.FALLING, callback = Shutdown, bouncetime = 2000)

# Now wait!
while 1:
    time.sleep(1)
    GPIO.output(24,GPIO.HIGH)

This is a 'true duct' frame for Emax BabyHawk flight gear (only) that offsets its weight with the thrust/efficiency gain inherent to ducted propellers. Version 1 has already been built and tested, and this is V2. This frame is printed in hollow single walls with expanding polyurethane foam injected post-printing for great strength. RCG thread is here: https://www.rcgroups.com/forums/showthread.php?2971472-23DT-the-3d-printed-Micro-130-with-true-ducts-Emax-BabyHawk-Gear

This version is still a work in progress -- I'm not super happy with the front clip area for the fuselage cover/lid. It prints kind of wonky but does work (the lid snaps in). UPDATE: The lid file I uploaded earlier was scaled for my printer. I have fixed the file. I also forgot to include the camera strap. All parts are updated now.

Highly recommend printing this in PETG since that gives the strength and flexibility needed. Please see RCG thread above for more details about the design and polyfoam injection, etc.

description.text:
This spool holder works well, but if you're as OCD as I am, you'll be annoyed that it twists a couple of degrees when there's a full spool on it because there's only support on one side. I'm looking into improvements so my spools (and yours!) can be perfectly square with the pegboard they're hanging on.

My work here is purely on the base. The two-piece screw that attaches to the spool is directly from jterranella's Pegboard Universal Spool Holder with no modifications whatsoever.

I recommend using 100mm M8 threaded rod as that will fit perfectly with no extra rod on either end.

Printer:

BIQU Kossel Plus

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Notes:

You'll need support since you're printing the pegs sideways. Everything else is pretty straightforward and up to your discretion.
Cleaning up the support around the pegs without damaging the pegs themselves can be a bit of a pain, but it's 30 seconds well spent to have strong clean pegs that fit in the holes and don't snap off.

I really like jterranella's Pegboard Universal Spool Holder, but I don't like that the base bolts together when it could be printed as one piece. It also bugged me that the outside surface where the 608 bearing meets the base has a recess in it so the outside of the bearing is rubbing against the plastic, defeating half the purpose of having the bearing.

I started with a 4x3 pegboard base using my Parametric Pegboard Base library, then added the angle frame using a linearly extruded polygon. From there, I reinforced the spool junction and added a small ridge that lines up with the inner bearing race so the outer race doesn't rub anymore.

top_ring.stl - .1mm layer height | 100% infill rectilinear
end_cap.stl - .2mm layer height | 15% infill 3d honeycomb
switch_cover.stl - .1mm layer height | 100% infill rectilinear
case.stl - .2mm layer height | 100% infill rectilinear

Assembly Parts List

The parts list for picture above.

Top Ring - top_ring.stl

Acrylic Lens - https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00YV5M7EM/ (cut to shape using dremel and bench grinder)

Bulb - https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01HB9WPAA (remove the springs)

Case - case.stl

Switch Cover - switch_cover.stl

Switch - https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00CQMG98W/

Body - body.stl

Battery - Uses a 18650 battery, I used https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00DUKCDDY

Spring - https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0085YWILC/

End Cap - end_cap.stl

TOOLS USED:
Dremel (used for cutting rough shape of lens on acrylic)
Bench Grinder (used for grinding rough acrylic lens into shape)
Hot Glue Gun (used to glue parts together)
Soldering Iron (used to solder wires)

Part 1 Part 1

Once all the parts have been assembled, solder a piece of wire onto the side of the bulb. Then place the bulb into the case.stl with the wire going through one of the openings.

Then, solder the wire to one of the contacts of the switch and fit the case.stl with the body.stl and place the switch into the designated slot. Use hot glue to secure them in place.

Part 2 Part 2

Now, solder a longer piece of wire onto the other contact of the switch. Put the wire through the bottom hole of end_cap.stl and solder it onto the spring (the spring can't be soldered on directly so a piece of copper wire was crimped to it using a small strip of tin and then soldered to make the contact secure). Then, fit the spring into the spring holding slot. Seal the hole with hot glue.

Part 3 Part 3

Fit the lens into top_ring.stl and then hot glue it onto body.stl

Part 4 Part 4

Hot glue the switch_cover.stl onto the switch.

title: Screwdriver Bit Clip for DeWalt Drill

description.text:
The DeWalt Li-Ion cordless drill (model DCD710) has become my "go to drill", favoring it over my larger models. It's very small, fits my hand well and is surprisingly powerful. My only complaint is that it lacks a clip to hold a screwdriver bit. This 3D part solves that by adding a screwdriver bit holder to the side of the drill.
STL along with Solidworks, OpenSCAD and Step design files are included.

The part was made on a MakerBot Replicator 2 with PLA filament.
The clip is printed with 2 shells, 15% infill, a 0.2mm layer height. It should be printed vertically (on its left side) so that no supports are needed.
It is attached to the drill's body using 13 small drops of superglue. There is a label on the drill at the location where the clip is mounted which should be removing first. I recommend clamping the part to the drill for 30 minutes while the superglue dries.

I wasn't happy with how "game accurate" the leg segments are so I am making a new version.
These are not designed to clip together and instead will rely on either a thick core copper wire inside or a piece of elastic to tension them.
They need the gold outline around the bottom, I am not sure about adding a thicker ridge or just using the paint to highlight. I've increased the height slightly since the (first, 3 segment) photo, they fit nicely but have a small range of motion. I need to print a load to see how well the leg bends overall.
The second photo shows the slightly taller segments arranged as a leg on the Guardian. The hip interface is there too and the whole leg is attached correctly. The range of motion seems to nearly match the other segment style (themselves a modification on the original).

I am exceedingly happy with how these look relative to the in game look of the guardian. When correctly painted they should be an extremely close match.

Original claw modded so it push fits into the last segment on the leg. Use either elastic or a wire as the core. Create a "knot" on one end, then thread the segments onto it. 14 segments and one interface joint. The claw will push onto the end of the leg and hide the inside of the last segment.
pull the elastic/wire tight inside the guardian and tie off, you can cross opposing side legs and twist together for good tension.

Now added a more accurate claw. Not flexible at all (yet) but should print easy and just push fit into the last section of leg.

I used 2mm aluminium Jewellery modelling wire inside the legs. Just a small 2mm long 90' bend at the end is enough to lock the segments on, then thread them all over with the hip joint interface last. Leave about 4-5cm of wire after the last part of the leg and push it into the hole on the body Hip joint. It needs to be a bit curved on the end to go all the way through but with some wiggling you can get it. once it's through pull it finger tight and then bend sharply against the plastic on the inside. If you bend upwards it should wedge into the inner shape nicely and lock the leg from wobbling. The whole leg is then able to be posed and 4 legs can take the guardians weight, maybe 3 even.

title: Anet A8 X-axis and Y-axis tensioners for 20T x 3mm toothed idlers

description.text:
I decided to upgrade my Anet A8 X-axis and Y-Axis belt tensioners for 20T x 3mm idlers.

Many discussions about which is better, smooth or toothed, but I'm not going to get into that here.

If you choose to go with 20T toothed, these prints will work well for you. You can get these 20T idlers from various places, Amazon, Gearbest, Banggood, Aliexpress, etc. As long as the width of the pulley is just under 9mm (pretty standard), these prints will work. Suggest to check the bearing smoothness of rotation by using the spindle bolt and nut lightly tightened, then rotation. Some of those bearings are either damaged on install or junk, so beware not to use ones that don't spin freely and get a few extras.

Props go out to:
X-axis tensionser concept from freemark

  • My design is completely new, but based on freemark's concept (improvements to accommodate the 20T pulley and X-axis belt clearance when belt is in "slack" mode.

Hardware needed:

  • M5x0.8mmx30mm bolts/screws (x2), M5x0.8mm nuts (x2, I chose Aero nuts to keep bolts fixed in place under vibration, but you can use regular nuts, if desired.)
  • For 20T pulley spindle, use M3x0.5mmx25mm or 30mm and nut. If you can find a M3 Aero nut, get that. Alternatively use 2 nuts and a dab of crazy glue on the flats to lock in place or loctite threadlocker.
    • Tighten the spindle screw sufficiently to achieve desired side lash and still turn freely.
    • Also, keep in mind that your X-axis belt length will become longer. If yours is too short, you will need to replace with a longer one. Good time to refresh your belt anyway.

Y-axis tensioner concept by CH35C0 for first posting the original and audiogod for the pushbar addition.

  • My remix is to increase the anchor clearance for the 20T idler, modify the pushbar to always stay in place with land area for the 8mm bolt end, modify the plate to accept the 8mm bolt thread, and knob for 8mm bolt. Don't bother trying to print simple hardware like threads (more of a headache and not durable).
  • Plate hole is proper size before tapping for M8x1.25mm thread. Carefully tap, slowly and straight in a vise. Look from 2 angles to assure going in straight during tapping, or you will have to print another one.
  • You will also need to print the front and rear frame supports from Leo_N to give support to your existing acrylic frame, if not already done so. If you don't, your stock frame will either bend or crack under increased belt tension.

Hardware needed:

  • M8x1.25mmx30mm bolt (x1)

All models printed at 0.2mm resolution and 100% infill, since somewhat structural.

Support definitely needed for the Y-axis anchor and plate printing. The other models are positioned to not need support.

Since 100% infill, make sure to use your best bed adhesion measures, as warping will be more a concern for the larger parts than if using some smaller infill values.

title: Magnet Seat Belt Adapter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This thing is a adapter to mount a magnetic phone mount to your seat belt. Have you ever been driving down the road, a phone call comes in and you answer it on speaker, but you can barely hear or the caller can barely hear you? As a result you have to pick the phone up and hold it to your face or find a better place for it. Well this thing solves that problem. I took a phone magnet for AC vent mounts and added it to a seat belt adapter. This thing will allow you to put your phone closer to your mouth and ear to better hear your phone call on speaker while still remaining hands free.

Currently this is designed to fit on a somewhat normal 47mm wide seat belt. If you have wider seat belts let me know and I can extend the width. I have included dimensions in the thing files.

There are two versions, one with holes that have recesses that fit the raised part on the back of the magnet and one w/out holes to mount the adhesive backed magnets.

Extra Hardware for Adapter w/ Holes
1x M3 washer
1x M3x12 Screw

Update: 10/22/2017
After some trials and a little use I made some adjustments to the adapter.
-Ridges to contact and hold the magnet.
-I have made slight changes to the thickness.
-All of the edges have been curved.
-Arms are tighter to reduce movement.
-Friction points on the inside of the adapter.

Alunar M505

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

For the adapter without holes use 10% as the layers are close enough that it will print the same with or without infill. The thing with holes is a little wider on the main face and does require some infill. Whether it's 10% or 100% it will print the same. I printed this with a brim to give a bigger foot print.

When printing this thing turn the model so it is printed longways along the Y-Axis. I ran into some consistent heating issues when printing on the x-axis. The model will work like a deflecting wall that will move excessive air onto the heated block causing the extruder to cool below the filament's melting point. Once the model was printed on the y-axis there were no problems at all.
